# Model Routing (R1-Q4)

## Tiered Model Strategy

| Task | Model | Cost Tier | When |
|------|-------|-----------|------|
| Brief expansion | Gemini Flash | $ | Always — structured output, high ROI |
| First-draft generation | Gemini Flash | $ | Always — 80% of ads are triaged here |
| Initial evaluation | Gemini Flash | $ | Always — good enough for triage scoring |
| Context distillation | Gemini Flash | $ | Always — small prompt, structured summary |
| Compliance check | Gemini Flash | $ | Always — binary decisions, low complexity |
| Improvable-range regen | Gemini Pro | $$$ | Only for 5.5–7.0 range ads |

## Score-Based Routing

```
Score ≥ 7.0  → PUBLISH (no regen needed, no model escalation)
Score 5.5–7.0 → ESCALATE to Gemini Pro (improvable range)
Score < 5.5  → DISCARD immediately (cheap exit)
```

The improvable range (5.5–7.0) is where Pro tokens have the highest marginal ROI. Concentrating expensive tokens here can reduce total spend 40–60% vs. using Pro everywhere.

## Model IDs

| Model | ID | Config Key |
|-------|-----|-----------|
| Gemini Flash | `gemini-2.0-flash` | `models.flash` |
| Gemini Pro | `gemini-2.5-pro` | `models.pro` |

Both via `google-genai` SDK using `GEMINI_API_KEY`.

## Routing Implementation

- `generate/model_router.py` owns routing logic (P1-06)
- Router receives the ad's current score + cycle number
- Returns model ID + generation parameters
- Every routing decision is logged in the ledger with `model_used`

## Do NOT

- Use Pro for first-draft generation — Flash is sufficient for triage
- Use Pro for ads scoring < 5.5 — they should be discarded, not rescued
- Hardcode model IDs — use `data/config.yaml`
- Route without logging the decision to the ledger
- Use any model outside Flash/Pro (no OpenAI, no Anthropic)
